LXXII. (Aa. 12. 16.)

CICERO ATTICO SAL.

Te tuis negotiis relictis nolo ad me venire. Ego potius accedam, si diutius impediere; etsi ne disces- sissem quidem e conspectu tuo, nisi me plane nihil ulla res adiuvaret. Quod si esset aliquod levamen, id esset in te un0, et cum primum ab aliquo poterit esse, a te erit. Nunc tamen ipsum sine te esse non possum.

LXXII. Astura, Mar. 10, 45 B.C. The death of his only daugh- ter, Tullia, in the latter part of Feb„ 45, robbed Cicero of the one person to whom he was deeply attached, and left him inconsola- ble. He betook himself at once to a house belonging to Atticus, near Rome, and then in a short time to his solitary villa upon the

island of Astura, where he re- mained alone, writing daily letters to Atticus (Att. 12. 9—44), and re- ceiving letters of condolence from Sulpicius, Dolabella, and other's. Cf. also Intr. 51, 53.
